The US Supreme Court heard arguments on the death penalty for minors, with international attention.
Attorney Seth Waxman argued against it, stating minors view risks differently.
Justice Breyer noted the trend against executing minors, while Benjamin believed age should be a factor.
Simmons denied scheming and boasted of escaping punishment.
Justices debated the maturity of juvenile criminals and the constitutionality of federal sentencing guidelines.
The court may abolish the death penalty for juveniles based on a national consensus.
The fate of the federal sentencing system hangs in the balance, impacting thousands of cases.
